Extracting the images and labels from the train and test datasets¶

Here we extract the features and labels into different variables. We also convert the data frame that is in the form of Tensors to numpy arrays using .numpy() - a tensorflow function.
Since colours aren't necessary for the dataset, we retain only the first of the three RGB channels (hence only R) using [:,:,0]. This allows us to retain the shape of the image as well as the first channel of its colours.
Shape is in the form (height, width, colour-channels)

Image and Label information can be found under the builder info tab. (Label consists of integers)

In [7]:
train_images = np.array([examples['image'].numpy()[:,:,0] for examples in train_data])
train_labels = np.array([examples['label'].numpy() for examples in train_data])

Not necessary but it is easier to work with when NN are concerned.

Neural Network Architecture¶

Using simple Neural Network

  • Two Fully connected layers
  • ReLu activation function at both FCs
  • Softmax activation on Output layer with 3 nodes corresponding to Rock, Paper or Scissors

The image is first flattened from (300, 300, 1) to a one dim. array of 300x300x1 ( = 90,000)

In [14]:

                          keras.layers.Flatten(),
                          keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
                          keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
                          keras.layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax')
])

model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss=keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

model.fit(train_images, train_labels, batch_size=32, epochs=5)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

The basic architecture is the same but we add multiple options for the Convolutional and Dense layers using the Choice or Int.

For the Convolutional layer, we choose between zero and 3 layers. The tuner automatically selects the most optimal number of layers to define. With the Dense layers, we specify different possible number of nodes at each layer, and here too the tuner selects the optimum number.

In [33]:
pip install -q -U keras-tuner
In [43]:
from kerastuner.tuners import RandomSearch

def build_model(hp):
  model = keras.Sequential()
  
  model.add(keras.layers.AveragePooling2D(6, 3, input_shape=(300,300,1)))

  for i in range(hp.Int("Conv Layers", min_value=0, max_value=3)):
    model.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(hp.Choice(f"layer_{i}_filters",[16, 32, 64]),kernel_size=3, activation='relu'))

  model.add(keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=2, strides=2))
  model.add(keras.layers.Dropout(0.5))
  model.add(keras.layers.Flatten())

  model.add(keras.layers.Dense(hp.Choice('Dense Layers',[64, 128, 512, 1024]), activation='relu'))

  model.add(keras.layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax'))


  model.compile(optimizer='adam',
                loss=keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                metrics=['accuracy'])
    
  return model
In [44]:
%%time
tuner = RandomSearch(
    build_model,
    objective = 'val_accuracy',
    max_trials = 32
)

tuner.search(train_images, train_labels,validation_data=(test_images, test_labels), epochs = 10, batch_size = 32)
